## 7. Ethical Considerations

> Bias risks, informed consent, privacy, potential harms, equity implications.
> Does this system reproduce or amplify existing disparities? Who bears the
> consequences when it fails?

The mobile app is funded by partnerships with high scoring water brands. This ensures accessibility, the app is offered for free, however, this partnership may introduce bias as high scoring brands may be scanned more often compared to those that are lower scoring. There is also the risk that the model may learn to bias based on water source (spring, purified municipal and artesian) if it develops the perception that one source tends to be better than others. The concern is that the model will favor one source or another and give it better scores. 
Access may be disproportional among communities with poor internet and electricity access, or those without smartphones that can connect to a 5G network. Access is also limited in non-English speaking communities. These communities tend to suffer from historical structural inequities and safe water access. For example, it is cultural practice in Mexican communities to drink only bottles water due to a poor perception of water safety. This type of tool would help these communities make better health safety decisions. Future developments of the app will need to include other languages starting with Spanish, Mandarin/Cantonese, Tagalog, Vietnamese, and Arabic, the top most spoken languages after English.
There is potential for harm if users make decisions based on scores that may be over a year old. More current issues may not be captured in the prediction, leaving people to make less well-informed health safety decisions. This is more impactful in vulnerable individuals, young children and immuno-compromised people. Ultimately, the responsible parties for ethical failures in the app are the water quality researchers at the University of Arizona. 

