## 8. Limitations & Caveats

> Known failure modes, edge cases, what the model does not capture. Conditions
> where it performs poorly. Assumptions baked into the design that may not
> hold in all deployment contexts.

While the model performs well under typical conditions, failures have been identified when there are conflicts in reported data, example the FDA data shows a brand is safe but independent labs find it to be unsafe. Failure also occurs when unusual inputs are reported for a brand or the combination of inputs is one the model has never seen (i.e. high arsenic + low turbidity+ E. coli present + no coliform detected). 
Assumption made by the model include 1)contaminants are tested consistently, 2)units and methods are standardized, and 3) data is accurate. These assumptions can create inaccuracy, especially if there are any rapid changes to any of those elements. 


---

## 9. Human Oversight

> Who reviews outputs before action is taken? Human in the loop, on the loop,
> or out of the loop? What is the escalation path when the model is wrong?
> Can it act autonomously — and should it?

This model maintains a human in the loop framework where the research group maintains general oversight and occasional field testing. The research group partners with a development team that surveys for bugs, corrupted code or dataset quality issues. The model can report to the developer when there is any critical failure like dataset availability or errors in score calculation, but ultimately is up to developers and researchers to maintain regular assessment to identify problems. The research team makes the final decision on how to handle any failures identified.

---

## 10. Temporal Validity

> When does this model need retraining or re-evaluation? What triggers a
> review — new data, policy change, population shift, outbreak? How does
> performance degrade over time?

Any changes in metrics tested, availability of the datasets, changes in frequency of reporting will trigger a review to ensure the model is able to make use of the best and most current data available. Changes to the maximum contaminant level regulations or water quality regulations will automatically trigger retaining to ensure the model has current data for comparison. Outdated data or comparison matrices will reduce the accuracy of the assessment and may result in significantly better or lower scores that do not represent reality.  
